<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-01-29T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-01-29T08:00:00-05:00" n="127" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d127">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">123J634/210: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="#p_JNT1" type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-01-29T21:00:00+08:00">January 29, 1932—9
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received January 29—6:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>146. I have just received the following telegram from the Acting Minister
                            of Foreign Affairs: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“In view of the very grave situation that has already developed
                                    in Shanghai I have the honor to request Your Excellency to come
                                    to Nanking at once. Please favor me with a reply. <persName corresp="#p_LW1">Lo Wen-kan</persName>.”</p></quote></p>
                        <p>I propose to leave here for Nanking Sunday evening, January 31st, taking
                                <persName corresp="#p_ECVH1">Engert</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_MEL1">Murray</persName>.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_JNT1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>